Fuck yeah, Kim Ogg
data.description:
I'm surprised this hasn't gotten more publicity outside of a few local articles and some pro-weed websites.

This is Kim Ogg, the new District Attorney in Houston, Texas. She campaigned on a platform that included reducing punishments for low level drug crimes, especially marijuana - her basic point was Houston has real problems, cops don't have time for this shit.

Last week, she, the mayor, and the new chief of police announced that if you are caught with under 4 ounces of weed, there is no arrest, no fine, no criminal record, nothing (other than they confiscate the weed). You just have to take a 4hr class and send in proof of completion and it's like it never happened. Essentially the same as going to traffic school for a speeding ticket.

For the uninformed, 4 ounces is a fuck ton. For personal use, most people buy an ounce or less at a time. So this not only covers personal use like some states that have decriminalized (though most of them do carry a $50 fine or so), it covers low level dealers too. The guy who buys a bunch to sell to his friends and coworkers - as long as he keeps it under 4oz - doesn't risk arrest.

Fuck yeah, Kim Ogg.

Edit: Police Chief Art Acevedo also deserves a big fuck yeah. Austin was sad to lose him, Houston is pumped to have him. This wouldn't be possible without his support. And similarly, fuck yeah Mayor Sylvester Turner who was also a instrumental in making this happen.

Source: http://www.click2houston.com/news/district-attorney-kim-ogg-unveils-misdemeanor-marijuana-diversion-program

data.description:
While working on the fourteenth floor some bricks I had to clear. Now to throw them down from such a height, was not a good idea. The foreman wasn't very pleased, he being an awkward sod. He said I'd have to carry them down the ladders in me hod. Now, clearing all these bricks by hand, it was so very slow. So I hoisted up a barrel, and secured the rope below. But in me haste to do the job, I was too blind to see;
That a barrel full of building bricks was heavier than me.

So when I untied the rope, the barrel fell like lead. And clinging tightly to the rope I started up instead. While I shot up like a rocket, to my dismay I found, that halfway up, I met the bloody barrel coming down. Well, the barrel broke my shoulders as to the ground it sped, and when I reached the top, I banged the pulley with me head. Well I clung on tight though numb and shock from this almighty blow, and the barrel spilled out half the bricks fourteen floors below.

Now, when these bricks had fallen from the barrel to the floor, I then outweighed the barrel, and so started down once more. Still clinging tightly to the rope, I sped towards the ground. And I landed on the broken bricks that were all scattered 'round.

While I lay their groaning on the ground I thought I passed the worst, when the barrel hit the pulley wheel, and then the bottom burst. Well a shower of bricks rained down on me - I hadn't got a hope.
As I lay there moaning on the ground: I let go of the bloody rope. The barrel then being heavier it started down once more, and landed right across me as I lay across the floor.Well it broke three ribs, and my left arm, and I can only say; that I hope you'll understand why Paddy's not at work today.
